          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">The family=E2=80=99=
s stock sales, no matter how inconsequential, came during a week when many =
of my conversations centered on Gap, J.Crew, Abercrombie, Victoria=E2=80=99=
s Secret, and the handful of brands that made the American mall as we envis=
ion it. I=E2=80=99m not sure how many of you are actually shopping at malls=
 these days, but the reality is that ultra-productive malls are filled with=
 Gucci and Louis Vuitton stores, with a sprinkling of Abercrombies. (A lot =
of the dead malls that you hear about are truly dead=E2=80=94and closed yea=
rs ago.)<br/><br/>The thing about the so-called mall brands is that, after =
years of bad headlines and doomsday scenarios, the ones that survived are m=
ostly faring relatively well. Gap projected a better-than-expected November=
 and December, causing shares to rise. Long-struggling Victoria=E2=80=99s S=
ecret raised its full-year outlook. (Shares are
up 80 percent this year.) Abercrombie &amp; Fitch=E2=80=99s shares, while n=
owhere near their peak, are up 70 percent year-to-date. J.Crew is a private=
 company and doesn=E2=80=99t disclose revenue figures, but walk into any st=
ore and it=E2=80=99s easy to see that people are buying the clothes. (In Au=
gust, there were <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6=
ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dUcmNfbk5FMy1IcnBGZ0V6R0VRRT0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDgtMDIvai1jcmV3LWV5ZX=
MtZGVidC1tYXJrZXQtcmV0dXJuLWFmdGVyLXVwZW5kaW5nLWxlbmRpbmcteWVhcnMtYWdvP3V0b=
V9jYW1wYWlnbj1MaW5lK1NoZWV0Ky0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4MTIlMkY5JTJGMjQlMjlcdTAw=
MjZ1dG1fY29udGVudD1MaW5lK1NoZWV0Ky0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4MTIlMkY5JTJGMjQlMjl=
cdTAwMjZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsX2FjdGlvblx1MDAyNnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3VzdG9tZXIuaW=
9cdTAwMjZ1dG1fdGVybT1mNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJpbnRlcm5hbCI6ImY2YzYwNjE3Z=
GE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImxpbmtfaWQiOjIwMTA1MjN9/5802465c0cb2b25d8a450c394ea6c6d905b=
c0e755c8ade314a1e9e81cd5f5df2" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:none;=
font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">reports</a></u> that the company was search=
ing for a $400 million loan after years of dodged defaults and a bankruptcy=
 that forced a new ownership structure. The company was able to refinance i=
ts existing loan in September=E2=80=94at a lower interest rate, even.) <br/=
><br/>The question, for me, is about their ceiling.
Abercrombie &amp; Fitch=E2=80=99s success in shifting the focus away from i=
ts heritage is clearly working with consumers, but there=E2=80=99s a limit =
to its trend-driven, fast-fashion-mimicking growth. The others are more rel=
iant on discounting. Profits at mall brands have eroded significantly over =
the past several decades as discounting culture in America has all but forc=
ed retailers to continually mark down. On Sunday, December 8, Gap.com=E2=80=
=99s sale was =E2=80=9Cup to 60 percent sitewide.=E2=80=9D Jcrew.com boaste=
d =E2=80=9Cup to 40 percent off our newest styles.=E2=80=9D Victoria=E2=80=
=99s Secret, a replenishment business that should theoretically <i>rarely</=
i> go on sale, was offering a 30 percent discount on<i> all</i> bras, its b=
read and butter. <br/><br/>There are two ways to think about discounting cu=
lture. One is to accept it, and simply factor consumer discounting expectat=
ions into the amount of product you have to sell in order to achieve certai=
n margins. (J.Crew=E2=80=99s Factory business, for instance, is growing
pretty rapidly as they continue to open new stores.) The problem with that =
way of thinking, of course, is that there are <i>far</i> larger volume play=
ers out there=E2=80=94Shein, Amazon, Uniqlo, etcetera. Analysts would prefe=
r that these mall brands sell less, more tightly curated product while focu=
sing on profit=E2=80=94the =E2=80=9Cshrink to grow=E2=80=9D theory. If you =
spoke to any of these companies=E2=80=99 top executives, most of them would=
 say that they are trying to do that. But it=E2=80=99s not easy when you al=
so have quarterly sales goals to hit, which helps to explain why they sell =
Gap clothing at Costco. <br/></td>
